-- U.S.-based stock funds post $7.6 bln outflows - Lipper
-- 
-- Thu May 22, 2014 06:21PM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, May 22 (Reuters) - Investors in U.S.-based funds pulled $7.6 billion out of stock funds in the week ended May 21, marking the biggest weekly net outflow from the funds since February, data from Thomson Reuters' Lipper service showed on Thursday.

Stock mutual funds attracted $2 billion in new cash, but stock exchange-traded funds posted $9.6 billion in outflows. Emerging market stock funds attracted $1.5 billion in inflows, their highest inflows in six weeks. Taxable bond funds attracted $3.4 billion in new cash, marking their 11th straight week of inflows. Riskier high-yield bond funds attracted $744 million, marking their biggest inflows since February.